&gt; We have used StrutsTestCase successfully on several medium- to large-
&gt; sized web projects with good success.
&gt; 
&gt; To overcome the problem you talk about (as well as other related 
&gt; ones), I have a custom subclass of MockStrutsTestCase that allows me 
&gt; to (optionally) set the action object I want the test to use.  
&gt; 
&gt; .public class AbstractStruts11TestCase extends MockStrutsTestCase {
&gt; .
&gt; .    /**
&gt; .     * Allow using a different action.  Checks to see if this action
&gt; .     * is assignment-compatbile with the action class mapped in 
&gt; .     * struts-config.
&gt; .     */
&gt; .    protected void setAction(Action other) {
&gt; .        String theActionPath = (String) getField(&quot;actionPath&quot;);
&gt; .        theRequestProcessor.setOverrideAction(other, theActionPath);
&gt; .    }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; This turns out to be very useful in a variety of situations.  I can 
&gt; subclass the Actions under test to override certain methods, etc.  
&gt; 
&gt; We also use this subclass to disable/enable the struts auto-
&gt; validation of form beans.  Sometimes you just want to test the action 
&gt; processing without worrying about if the form is valid or not.  
&gt; 
&gt; I would be happy to send you the code if you think this would be 
&gt; useful.
&gt; 
&gt; Jeff Nielsen
&gt; Digital Focus
&gt; www.digitalfocus.com
&gt; 
&gt; 
